<html>
  <head>
    <!-- from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2011142/how-to-change-the-style-of-the-title-attribute-inside-an-anchor-tag -->
    <style type="text/css">
      html {
          font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
          font-size: 12pt;
      }

      [data-title]:hover:after {
          opacity: 1;
          transition: all 0.1s ease 0.5s;
          visibility: visible;
      }
      [data-title]:after {
          content: attr(data-title);
          background-color: #00FF00;
          color: #111;
          font-size: 150%;
          position: absolute;
          padding: 1px 5px 2px 5px;
          bottom: -1.6em;
          left: 100%;
          white-space: nowrap;
          box-shadow: 1px 1px 3px #222222;
          opacity: 0;
          border: 1px solid #111111;
          z-index: 99999;
          visibility: hidden;
      }
      [data-title] {
          position: relative;
      }
    </style>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="./test.css">
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      This is text with <a href="#" data-title="D999">a link hover</a>
    </p>
  </body>
</html>
```

	- immediately BEFORE the Stripe call that does the charge, do a database txn that writes an "in progress" value to that field; 

- immediately AFTER a successful call, change the value to the transaction ID;

- immediately AFTER a failed call, clear the value in preparation for trying again.

since the time to do the Stripe call itself is typically just a few seconds, there could be a "sweeper" that runs every few minutes (as it does already for sweeping stale orders, etc) and sends up a flare if it finds any in-progress orders that have an "in progress" value older than a minute or so.  the flare could consist of an email to us, or to the boxoffice, or whatever.

if one is found, i believe Stripe has a "comments" field for each charge transaction and we are using it to record (among other things) the order ID within A1, so the "flare" should be able to identify or help search for the Stripe txn associated with the not-completed order.
